1. Setup Environment

Make sure your system has the following installed:

gcc (i386 cross-compiler recommended)

nasm

ld (from binutils)

grub-mkrescue

qemu

Check installation:

gcc --version
nasm -v
ld --version
grub-mkrescue --version
qemu-system-i386 --version

2. Prepare Project Folder

Your folder should contain:

my-simple-os/
│
├── boot.asm
├── kernel.c
├── linker.ld
├── Makefile      (optional, but recommended)


boot.asm → Bootloader

kernel.c → Kernel with Day 2 keyboard input

linker.ld → Linker script

3. Compile Kernel and Bootloader

If you have a Makefile:

make


If no Makefile, manually compile:

# Compile kernel C file
gcc -m32 -ffreestanding -O2 -c kernel.c -o kernel.o

# Assemble bootloader
nasm -f elf32 boot.asm -o boot.o

# Link everything
ld -m elf_i386 -T linker.ld -o kernel.bin boot.o kernel.o

4. Create ISO for GRUB

Create the folder structure for GRUB:

mkdir -p isodir/boot/grub
cp kernel.bin isodir/boot/


Create grub.cfg:

echo 'set timeout=0
set default=0
menuentry "MyOS" {
    multiboot /boot/kernel.bin
    boot
}' > isodir/boot/grub/grub.cfg


Build ISO:

grub-mkrescue -o os.iso isodir

5. Run OS in QEMU

Boot the ISO:

qemu-system-i386 -cdrom os.iso


You should see:

Day 2 OS: Type something!


Press keys — they should appear on screen.

6. Optional: Test Shell Commands

If you added simple shell functionality:

Type help → shows available commands

Type clear → clears the screen

7. Exit QEMU

Close the QEMU window normally

Or press Ctrl + A then X

8. Cleanup (Optional)

Remove build files if needed:

rm *.o kernel.bin
rm -r isodir
